WEBVTT

1
00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:20.570
For hundreds of centuries andlong after men had settled inthe land masses of Europe,

2
00:00:20.570 --> 00:00:22.370
Asia and Africa,

3
00:00:22.370 --> 00:00:26.700
this continent was unknown toany human being.

4
00:02:06.330 --> 00:02:09.600
In swamps and valleys the sizeof Scotland

5
00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:13.600
animals unknown in Europedisturbed only each other.

6
00:02:32.070 --> 00:02:42.700
Strange birds of prey wheeledsafely over an empty continent.

7
00:02:42.700 --> 00:02:46.770
At some point, we suppose notlater than 15,000 BC,

8
00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:50.330
humans drifted down from Asiaand the Aleutians,

9
00:02:50.330 --> 00:02:52.500
ranged the length and breadth ofthe Americas,

10
00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:56.600
built and exhaustedcivilizations we know nothingabout.

11
00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:59.400
Today there are only a fewancient relics,

12
00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:03.470
such as this one in a remotecanyon of northern Arizona.

13
00:03:05.030 --> 00:03:09.270
There were nations that neverknew each other, five hundredlanguages,

14
00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:16.900
tribes that worshipped a bison,or a matriarch, or the corn theygrew.

15
00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:20.400
There were tribes ruled bywarriors;

16
00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:28.670
or by women farmers;

17
00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:37.570
or by sacred elders.

18
00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:48.530
Tribes that had never heard ofwar

19
00:03:48.530 --> 00:03:53.530
and tribes debauched bycenturies of fighting.

20
00:04:05.170 --> 00:04:10.630
Hollywood has often restaged thesight and sound of imaginarydances

21
00:04:10.630 --> 00:04:15.630
but those sounds you hear arenot those of 25-dollar a dayIndian extras.

22
00:04:23.970 --> 00:04:28.570
These are Apaches of the 1970's,for once in their history

23
00:04:28.570 --> 00:04:32.370
allowing us to watch all but themost sacred moments

24
00:04:32.370 --> 00:04:36.600
of an annual ceremony in whichsupernatural figures celebrate

25
00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:40.600
the passage of their women fromchildhood to puberty.

26
00:04:54.970 --> 00:05:01.030
So for at least 150 centuriesbefore Yankee Doodle theirs wasthe American Way of Life.

27
00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:09.900
But for better or worse this iswhat we've made of it.

28
00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:14.130
And it is the past four-hundredyears that we think of as thehistory

29
00:05:14.130 --> 00:05:17.130
of the land that becamethe United States.

30
00:05:30.770 --> 00:05:34.800
I've been discovering thathistory for 40 years of reading

31
00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:37.600
and travel throughout the UnitedStates,

32
00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:40.370
and for 20 of those years I'velived here in this apartment

33
00:05:40.370 --> 00:05:43.730
which overlooks Central Park inNew York City.

34
00:05:43.730 --> 00:05:50.400
For most of my time as a foreigncorrespondent this has been mydaily map of the United States

35
00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:52.100
- and I mean literally a map.

36
00:05:52.100 --> 00:05:56.730
I once had a secretary who washopeless at geography and tohelp her -

37
00:05:56.730 --> 00:05:58.530
and me find the right books,

38
00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:02.800
I arranged them in this order;everything on New England is inthe north-east corner.

39
00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:04.800
You go right down the coast toFlorida.

40
00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:07.300
Across the Deep South, the SouthWest to California.

41
00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:13.430
Up to Oregon, Washington -andyou have to have high boots toreach Alaska.

42
00:06:13.430 --> 00:06:17.000
Now, because of a continuinginterest in California history,

43
00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.070
California tends to go half wayacross the country

44
00:06:19.070 --> 00:06:26.230
and spill right over into Texas,rather like a Californian'smental map of the United States.

45
00:06:26.230 --> 00:06:31.370
Well, we all lay great stress onour favorite states and placesand people.

46
00:06:31.370 --> 00:06:33.930
Don't be upset if some of yoursget squeezed out.

47
00:06:33.930 --> 00:06:38.370
I have a man I'm mad about -overthere - Benjamin Franklin,

48
00:06:38.370 --> 00:06:42.230
and I'm not sure that even hewill make it.

49
00:06:42.230 --> 00:06:46.400
You know, when I told an oldSoutherner, a friend of mine,that I was going to try

50
00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:56.270
and tell my version of Americanhistory in thirteen hours, hesaid 'better talk fast boy'.

51
00:06:56.270 --> 00:07:00.100
So we ought to begin with thesimple colossal question

52
00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:03.130
who was the first white man todiscover America,

53
00:07:03.130 --> 00:07:08.400
which incidentally was namedafter a Florentine business manand promoter,

54
00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:13.700
who promoted himself so well asto get his first name attachedto a continent,

55
00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:17.300
he was Amerigo Vespucci.

56
00:07:17.300 --> 00:07:21.130
He took no part in the earlyvoyages, so who was the first?

57
00:07:21.130 --> 00:07:24.000
Well, there are people who arehot for the Vikings;

58
00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.530
now we hear that the Phoenicianswere here first;

59
00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:32.600
no, the Jews - who presumablytook one look at New York Cityand beat it back to the Nile.

60
00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:38.500
The records of the earliestvoyages are either lost, orhighly debatable.

61
00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:44.970
But there was one historicexpedition which is documentedbeyond all question.

62
00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:46.900
Which is why we're going into mykitchen.

63
00:07:50.630 --> 00:07:53.900
You know, some of the greatexplosions of history have beencaused

64
00:07:53.900 --> 00:08:02.470
by nothing more than thedenial of a simple human need.

65
00:08:02.470 --> 00:08:11.170
Like a shortage of water, or toomany people in a small country,a total absence of timber,

66
00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:20.230
which has plagued the Egyptianssince the time of Solomon.

67
00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:24.900
Today we think of these spices-pepper, paprika,

68
00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:30.070
cinnamon, cloves - as no morethan gilt to the lily.

69
00:08:30.070 --> 00:08:33.530
But in the 15th century theywere what made food edible.

70
00:08:33.530 --> 00:08:36.130
They had salt but no other wayof preserving food,

71
00:08:36.130 --> 00:08:39.530
and even in rich houses, itoften came to the table putrid,

72
00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:43.130
so these spices deceived thepalate,

73
00:08:43.130 --> 00:08:47.070
if not the digestion, which theysometimes still do.

74
00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:51.930
Now, in 1453 the Turks conqueredConstantinople

75
00:08:51.930 --> 00:08:54.530
(our Istanbul) and it was thegateway to Asia.

76
00:08:54.530 --> 00:09:00.170
So what they'd done was to shutoff Europe from Asia, which waswhere the spices came from.

77
00:09:00.170 --> 00:09:06.430
That's to say from here -fromthe Molucca Islands betweenBorneo and the Philippines.

78
00:09:06.430 --> 00:09:11.430
It's astounding to me that thename -the Moluccas -is not asfamous as London or Boston,

79
00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:14.330
because they were the SpiceIslands where the natives grew

80
00:09:14.330 --> 00:09:20.470
and packed their preciousproducts for the Turks and forEurope.

81
00:09:20.470 --> 00:09:25.300
How to reach them, exceptthrough Constantinople?

82
00:09:25.300 --> 00:09:29.200
There was a superb sailor, anItalian who not only thought heknew how,

83
00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:31.870
but was determined to do ithimself.

84
00:09:31.870 --> 00:09:34.930
For many years a master marinerwith the Portuguese,

85
00:09:34.930 --> 00:09:37.330
who then had the best merchantmarine in Europe,

86
00:09:37.330 --> 00:09:42.230
he had spent much time withastronomers and mathematicianswho believed,

87
00:09:42.230 --> 00:09:47.530
unlike many sailors, that theearth was round.

88
00:09:47.530 --> 00:09:50.270
The known map of the world was asingle land mass

89
00:09:50.270 --> 00:09:55.770
as flat as a pancake with theunknown Ocean Sea around it.

90
00:09:55.770 --> 00:10:01.030
But if it was a sphere you couldobviously sail from the Westernextreme to the eastern,

91
00:10:01.030 --> 00:10:08.330
to Japan, China and Indonesia,to the Indies where the spiceslay.

92
00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:16.930
So thought Cristoforo Colombo.This tough, passionate Christianheld visionary talks with god,

93
00:10:16.930 --> 00:10:22.200
but they did not cloud hisinstinct for ten per cent -whichwas what he demanded and got,

94
00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:25.500
for all the loot of the lands hemight discover.

95
00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:30.670
After a 15 years trek aroundEurope, he found his sponsors inthe King and Queen of Spain

96
00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:34.900
who coveted the spice trade,needed gold for their dwindlingtreasury,

97
00:10:34.900 --> 00:10:38.500
and shared Columbus'shorror of the infidel Turk.

98
00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:43.130
So they packed him off on hismission 'for gospel and forgold.'

99
00:10:43.130 --> 00:10:48.070
And here in Barcelona harbor isa replica of the ship in whichColumbus sailed,

100
00:10:48.070 --> 00:10:49.500
the Santa Maria.

101
00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:52.330
Today it would not be acceptableas a yacht

102
00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:55.400
by any self-respecting member ofthe jet set.

103
00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:58.770
One hundred tons only and 75feet long,

104
00:10:58.770 --> 00:11:02.300
it was not by a longshot one of the big ships of thetime,

105
00:11:02.300 --> 00:11:06.370
but it would have to be sturdyenough to withstand roaringstorms

106
00:11:06.370 --> 00:11:12.470
and quick enough to take shelterin the shallow channels of theimagined Atlantic Islands.

107
00:11:12.470 --> 00:11:14.570
It was payed with pitch againstbarnacles,

108
00:11:14.570 --> 00:11:18.670
had stones for ballast and amain mast as long as the keel.

109
00:11:18.670 --> 00:11:22.670
The other two ships were smallerstill.

110
00:11:29.530 --> 00:11:36.400
Here in the stern is Columbus'scabin and his bed.

111
00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:41.670
Incidentally he was six feet,which in those days wasenormous,

112
00:11:41.670 --> 00:11:47.900
and by the time he landed hemust have been permanently bentover.

113
00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:49.830
And here he would have hischarts.

114
00:11:49.830 --> 00:11:53.230
He'd been in the chartbusiness with his brother foryears

115
00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:56.700
and, an odd detail about theprovisions.

116
00:11:56.700 --> 00:12:00.330
Naturally they carried red winewhich was a standard laxative,

117
00:12:00.330 --> 00:12:07.600
but two-and-a-half liters perman per day, which sounds likean awful lot.

118
00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:12.100
I suppose they meant it to keepthem philosophical if the worsthappened.

119
00:12:12.100 --> 00:12:17.700
There were forty men aboard,including a surgeon and theKing's Controller of Accounts,

120
00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:23.100
to keep tabs on Columbus'sswindle sheets when he startedto figure the cost of the gold

121
00:12:23.100 --> 00:12:25.830
and the spices he was going totake.

122
00:12:25.830 --> 00:12:29.370
There was a converted Jew whospoke Arabic,

123
00:12:29.370 --> 00:12:33.500
which they thought was verysimilar to Chinese and so he'dbe the interpreter.

124
00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:38.200
One Portuguese, another Italianand the rest were Spaniards.

125
00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:46.530
And so on the evening of the 2ndAugust 1492 the entire crew wentashore for confession,

126
00:12:46.530 --> 00:12:49.530
received absolution for theirsins,

127
00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:53.200
and on the morning of the 3rd,they set sail from Palos.

128
00:13:10.030 --> 00:13:12.800
They sailed all through Augustand September

129
00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:15.570
and saw none of the islandsthey'd expected.

130
00:13:15.570 --> 00:13:19.770
The crews grew weary, thennervous, then panicky and wereclose to mutiny.

131
00:13:19.770 --> 00:13:24.030
Maybe the world wasn't round.Maybe they'd fall off intospace.

132
00:13:24.030 --> 00:13:27.170
The two other captains beggedColumbus to turn back.

133
00:13:27.170 --> 00:13:32.700
He had drastically miscalculatedby about eighty per cent thewidth of the Ocean Sea,

134
00:13:32.700 --> 00:13:36.870
so he faked the log by reducingthe mileage they'd gone fromSpain.

135
00:13:36.870 --> 00:13:42.600
And to redress this deceit hetells us 'he pray'd mightily tothe Lord'.

136
00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:48.070
Well, by Divine Intervention -orluck - on the following day, the12th October,

137
00:13:48.070 --> 00:13:56.970
he sighted as he believed themainland of Asia or one of itsoffshore islands.

138
00:13:56.970 --> 00:14:03.770
We know it was San Salvador, inthe Bahamas, and he went on toexplore Haiti and Cuba.

139
00:14:03.770 --> 00:14:07.730
Like most eager travelers,Columbus found what he waslooking for.

140
00:14:07.730 --> 00:14:13.600
He decided that Cuba was Japan.He was a little baffled by theabsence of cities.

141
00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:18.200
But there were spices, andcotton, and weird birds andcoppery colored natives

142
00:14:18.200 --> 00:14:24.230
who kept assuring him there weremountains of gold inland. Alwaysfurther inland.

143
00:14:24.230 --> 00:14:25.070
If this was so

144
00:14:25.070 --> 00:14:30.970
the slaves to work the goldmines were already on hand inthese peaceable natives.

145
00:14:30.970 --> 00:14:35.370
He was almost convinced and likea good salesman he hurried backto Spain

146
00:14:35.370 --> 00:14:40.630
with what we should call displaysamples of the products he'dgathered;

147
00:14:40.630 --> 00:14:44.170
exotic plants, an alligator,brilliant parrots,

148
00:14:44.170 --> 00:14:53.100
prize natives got up like showhorses, some gold.

149
00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:59.200
Columbus's sales exhibition wasa total success and his nextfleet was 17 ships

150
00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:05.530
and fifteen hundred men,sailors, soldiers, adventurers,rushed to found gold

151
00:15:05.530 --> 00:15:07.170
and silver mining colonies,

152
00:15:07.170 --> 00:15:12.730
and there was a clutch ofpriests along to sanctify thenecessary slaves.

153
00:15:12.730 --> 00:15:18.130
But this time he really did findgold. And there now began thelongest,

154
00:15:18.130 --> 00:15:23.870
the most determined and the mostbrutal, gold rush in history.

155
00:15:23.870 --> 00:15:28.570
If the natives were sulky orhostile they were terrified intosubmission

156
00:15:28.570 --> 00:15:31.370
by two acts of magicthat they'd never seen.

157
00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:37.730
One was the firing of monstermachines called cannons, and theother was the appearance -

158
00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:43.400
and this always worked of livingmonsters called horses.

159
00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:49.300
There were many brave priestsalong who were sickened by theoutrages along the trail.

160
00:15:49.300 --> 00:15:54.530
And there's an unforgettablestory of a native king who wasabout to be burned at the stake,

161
00:15:54.530 --> 00:15:57.430
and as he felt the first firesrise on his body,

162
00:15:57.430 --> 00:16:01.900
he refused baptism on thegrounds that he might go toheaven

163
00:16:01.900 --> 00:16:06.330
'and meet there onlyChristians'.

164
00:16:06.330 --> 00:16:10.830
Within fifty years of Columbussighting San Salvador theSpaniards had plundered

165
00:16:10.830 --> 00:16:14.030
and conquered the whole ofCentral America and Peru.

166
00:16:14.030 --> 00:16:18.870
Now the Pope had proclaimed thateverything one hundred leagueswest of the Azores

167
00:16:18.870 --> 00:16:21.830
belonged to Spain or her brotherPortugal.

168
00:16:21.830 --> 00:16:27.070
But some nations refused to bowto this proclamation, mostdramatically the King of France.

169
00:16:27.070 --> 00:16:33.570
"We fail", he said, "to findthis clause in Adam's will".

170
00:16:33.570 --> 00:16:36.800
The first French arrivals onlytwelve years after Columbus

171
00:16:36.800 --> 00:16:41.530
were Breton fishermen workingthe cod banks off Nova Scotia.

172
00:16:41.530 --> 00:16:46.200
But they soon came on Indianseager to barter furs for bits ofmetal and gunpowder,

173
00:16:46.200 --> 00:16:51.000
so they abandoned the cod,penetrated the Gulf and theRiver St. Lawrence

174
00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:55.700
and trapped and skinned everyanimal in sight.

175
00:16:55.700 --> 00:16:58.070
These humble trappers wereincidentally

176
00:16:58.070 --> 00:17:02.130
putting out the tentacles of theFrench Empire in the north.

177
00:17:06.430 --> 00:17:09.170
While down in Mexico City,Cortes,

178
00:17:09.170 --> 00:17:14.570
a penniless noblemanturned soldier was crowninghimself as a Mexican God.

179
00:17:14.570 --> 00:17:18.170
The Spaniards were now ready toinvestigate their favorite myth

180
00:17:18.170 --> 00:17:23.370
that to the north lay sevencities of gold.

181
00:17:23.370 --> 00:17:25.370
So in 1540 another soldier,

182
00:17:25.370 --> 00:17:30.530
Francisco Vasquez de Coronado,marched north to find them.

183
00:17:30.530 --> 00:17:33.200
He started from Mexico withthree hundred men,

184
00:17:33.200 --> 00:17:39.200
a horde of Indians, hundreds ofhorses, mules, cattle, sheep,goats and priests.

185
00:17:39.200 --> 00:17:42.330
They marched for two years goingup through Arizona

186
00:17:42.330 --> 00:17:45.270
and New Mexico and Texas,wheeling north-east

187
00:17:45.270 --> 00:17:49.200
into the middle of the presentstate of Kansas.

188
00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:56.770
To us their expectations seempreposterous based on a wholeSpanish literature

189
00:17:56.770 --> 00:18:01.100
which said that North Americacontained volcanoes andmermaids,

190
00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:07.070
and was the place where Judastook his annual winter vacationfrom the fires of hell.

191
00:18:07.070 --> 00:18:10.670
Also the splendid golden objectsthat abounded in Central America

192
00:18:10.670 --> 00:18:15.330
were said to hang in the northfrom trees.

193
00:18:15.330 --> 00:18:19.800
They found no cities, no gold,much less trees to hang it on.

194
00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:23.900
Nothing but an endless lunarlandscape.

195
00:18:51.830 --> 00:18:54.400
But these were the rigors of thesoldier's lot.

196
00:18:54.400 --> 00:19:00.470
Their one consolation was thatthe native humans at least couldbe conquered and hired to serve.

197
00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:06.370
But once they came on aseemingly invincible pueblo.

198
00:19:06.370 --> 00:19:12.370
It was a mountain stronghold ofhostile Indians, and it wascalled Acoma.

199
00:19:26.670 --> 00:19:30.130
The first white man to see itwas a scout from Coronado'sexpedition.

200
00:19:30.130 --> 00:19:34.370
He went back and he told hiscommander of a 'great city inthe sky'.

201
00:19:34.370 --> 00:19:38.370
The strongest position hereported ever seen in the world.

202
00:19:45.130 --> 00:19:49.130
The Acoma Indians have livedhere for at least a thousandyears.

203
00:19:49.130 --> 00:19:51.670
On their sheer pathways up therock

204
00:19:51.670 --> 00:19:58.030
countless hands have worndown cracks into smoothhandholds.

205
00:19:58.030 --> 00:20:03.530
On such a climb an armor-cladsoldier was a pretty poor matchfor a nimble redskin.

206
00:20:03.530 --> 00:20:08.770
Coronado surveyed it from afarand gave it a miss.

207
00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:11.030
To this day the elders of theAcomas,

208
00:20:11.030 --> 00:20:15.230
unlike many Indian tribes,refuse to yield their ancientways,

209
00:20:15.230 --> 00:20:17.370
or to perform for thewhite man.

210
00:20:17.370 --> 00:20:23.370
They forbid all strangers toenter or see these sacred placescalled Kiva.

211
00:20:40.170 --> 00:20:42.130
No power lines may be laid,

212
00:20:42.130 --> 00:20:47.170
no artificial heat of any kindis available even for the bakingof bread,

213
00:20:47.170 --> 00:20:52.530
Not for want of money butbecause the rock on which thecity itself is built is sacred

214
00:20:52.530 --> 00:20:55.530
and may not be broken or defiledin any way.

215
00:21:03.300 --> 00:21:07.270
This old man, 30 miles away frommotels, pizza parlors

216
00:21:07.270 --> 00:21:11.670
and Jo's second-hand car lot, isadding an extra room to hishouse

217
00:21:11.670 --> 00:21:16.000
with no help from the techniquesof the American way of life.

218
00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:24.900
How about the young? They lookAmerican, they talk American,

219
00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:29.670
and today they are learning thattheir heritage is one ofbetrayal.

220
00:21:29.670 --> 00:21:35.330
This may be the last generationwilling to walk the olduncomplaining ways.

221
00:22:27.900 --> 00:22:31.870
Well, this windswept fortresswhich is at the top of thecontinental divide

222
00:22:31.870 --> 00:22:37.430
remained unconquered for 59years after Coronado had seenit.

223
00:22:37.430 --> 00:22:42.370
And then the Spaniards mounted athree-day and night assault andthey took it.

224
00:22:42.370 --> 00:22:47.370
It was a feat sufficient toprovoke in a soldier-poet astill celebrated epic poem.

225
00:22:47.370 --> 00:22:53.870
And certainly the Spanish tookan epic revenge; six hundredprisoners, six hundred killed,

226
00:22:53.870 --> 00:22:57.970
they took the leading 70warriors and tossed them off thetop of the cliff.

227
00:22:57.970 --> 00:23:03.330
They bound to life-timeservitude another five hundredmostly women and children.

