00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:48.930
is likely to become a waystation or a camp ground.

246
00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:57.730
It's odd that the first whitemen on the march through Americashould have yielded to that

247
00:24:57.730 --> 00:25:02.230
curious human itch which hasafflicted tourists in the GreekIslands,

248
00:25:02.230 --> 00:25:08.700
the Grand Canyon andDisneyland, to write up their names on a stone.

249
00:25:08.700 --> 00:25:12.670
It's odder still that suchinscriptions should survive in acountry

250
00:25:12.670 --> 00:25:18.630
which tears down a skyscraperwhich is less than a quarter ofa century old.

251
00:25:18.630 --> 00:25:23.700
At any rate the first man whocarved himself into immortality

252
00:25:23.700 --> 00:25:31.400
and we think probably with thepoint of a sword -was this one;'Paso pora qui el arrivantando'

253
00:25:31.400 --> 00:25:33.900
through here passed thegovernor,

254
00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:41.900
Don Juan de Onyate after hisdiscovery of the Sea of theSouth, April 16th 1605.'

255
00:25:41.900 --> 00:25:47.530
Now by the Sea of the South, hemeant that he'd been as far asthe Gulf of California,

256
00:25:47.530 --> 00:25:52.670
and like every other Spaniardwho ever saw a body of waterthat was seemingly endless,

257
00:25:52.670 --> 00:25:55.830
he thought he'd found thatpassage through to the Pacific.

258
00:25:55.830 --> 00:25:59.870
He did set up the first Spanishgovernment in the South West,

259
00:25:59.870 --> 00:26:02.930
and here is his palace atSanta Fe.

