00:26:07.730 --> 00:26:14.400
It was built 10 years before thePilgrim Fathers landed on theNew England coast.

261
00:26:14.400 --> 00:26:19.930
For the next two hundred yearsthese remote provinces of NewSpain today's Texas,

262
00:26:19.930 --> 00:26:26.270
Arizona, California -slowlydeveloped an outpost economythroughout a burning landscape

263
00:26:26.270 --> 00:26:29.270
half the size of Europe.

264
00:26:43.570 --> 00:26:48.270
The Spanish had introduced twoindispensable elements ofWestern life;

265
00:26:48.270 --> 00:26:51.970
the horse and the cow.

266
00:26:51.970 --> 00:26:56.430
It was the horse that had firstterrified the Western Indianinto submission.

267
00:26:56.430 --> 00:27:04.530
It was the horse that was to sethim free, and free-wheeling fromMexico to the Canadian tundra.

268
00:27:04.530 --> 00:27:07.270
And the Spanish left behind inthe branding signs

269
00:27:07.270 --> 00:27:13.330
and the embossing of saddles awhole heraldry of ranching.

270
00:27:13.330 --> 00:27:15.470
I imagine that those of us bornabroad

271
00:27:15.470 --> 00:27:20.030
think of a rodeo as aWestern circus for the public'sentertainment.

272
00:27:20.030 --> 00:27:25.170
But throughout two thousandmiles. the whole arc of thesouthwest a rodeo -

273
00:27:25.170 --> 00:27:30.170
literally a round-up - is one ofthe timeless chores of ranching.

274
00:27:55.600 --> 00:27:59.270
The word 'cowboy' is directlytranslated from 'vaquero'.

275
00:27:59.270 --> 00:28:02.970
On this ranch in Arizona allthese men speak only Spanish,

276
00:28:02.970 --> 00:28:08.770
except the ranch owner and hisforeman, known as the 'maja' ormajor domo.

277
00:28:08.770 --> 00:28:12.670
And their equipment retains theSpanish names; the lariat;

278
00:28:12.670 --> 00:28:26.530
the chaps they wear forprotection against the desertscrub called chaperral

279
00:28:26.530 --> 00:28:29.830
The purpose of the rodeo wasto round up once a year

