00:33:05.370 --> 00:33:07.470
Certainly only they and laterthe Scots

314
00:33:07.470 --> 00:33:11.470
would have knotted alifeline across a continent oftundra.

315
00:33:15.470 --> 00:33:19.930
One of the epic French journeysof exploration began in November1678

316
00:33:19.930 --> 00:33:26.400
when a young nobleman, ReneCavelier Sieur de la Salle, setsail across Lake Ontario.

317
00:33:26.400 --> 00:33:30.670
He was seeking a way southacross the continent by water.

318
00:33:34.070 --> 00:33:36.570
His boat was wrecked and inmid-winter

319
00:33:36.570 --> 00:33:41.070
his expedition had todrag its equipment aroundNiagara Falls.

320
00:33:41.070 --> 00:33:44.770
Despite many disasters, and tothe wonderment of the SenecaIndians,

321
00:33:44.770 --> 00:33:48.430
they managed in the spring of1679 to build another boat

322
00:33:48.430 --> 00:33:54.700
and launched it on Lake Erie,where no ship had ever sailed.

323
00:33:54.700 --> 00:33:58.170
In it, La Salle sailed acrossthe Great Lakes, over Lake Erie,

324
00:33:58.170 --> 00:34:00.800
up the St. Clair, up Lake Huron,westward

325
00:34:00.800 --> 00:34:02.230
into Lake Michigan.

326
00:34:02.230 --> 00:34:08.370
Battling hunger and appallingweather they reached theIllinois River.

327
00:34:08.370 --> 00:34:11.570
The boat sank. They met and hadto fight hostile Indians,

328
00:34:11.570 --> 00:34:16.270
and la Salle was plagued withdebts and doubters back home.

329
00:34:16.270 --> 00:34:20.900
In the winter they had to dragtheir supplies overland, thegoing so bad

330
00:34:20.900 --> 00:34:25.270
that they wore out a pair ofleather moccasins every day.

331
00:34:25.270 --> 00:34:29.600
But eventually they reached openwater on a branch of theIllinois River.

332
00:34:29.600 --> 00:34:34.130
And on the 6th February 1682they floated into theMississippi

333
00:34:34.130 --> 00:34:36.930
and fifteen hundred miles downthe great river,

334
00:34:36.930 --> 00:34:42.000
until after two months theyreached the open sea.

335
00:34:43.670 --> 00:34:47.800
On the 9th April La Salleassembled his men, raised across

336
00:34:47.800 --> 00:34:50.730
and the banner of France, and inthe name of Louis X1Vth,

337
00:34:50.730 --> 00:34:58.870
he took possession of all thevast lands he had covered andcalled them Louisiana.

338
00:34:58.870 --> 00:35:01.030
La Salle was killed on a laterexpedition

339
00:35:01.030 --> 00:35:05.330
but in time the French built theport of New Orleans at the mouthof the Mississippi.

340
00:35:05.330 --> 00:35:15.270
Yet they never domesticated theenormous hinterland La Salle hadbrought them.

341
00:35:15.270 --> 00:35:19.530
Here is a French map of themid-eighteenth century, 1755,

342
00:35:19.530 --> 00:35:24.270
which shows what an exclusivehold the French had in thenorth,

343
00:35:24.270 --> 00:35:30.030
what an accurate picture of whatyou might call lateral America.

344
00:35:30.030 --> 00:35:34.030
But you see the French were justas vague about what lay to thesouth

345
00:35:34.030 --> 00:35:39.830
and west as the Spanish had beenabout what lay to their northand west.

346
00:35:39.830 --> 00:35:43.200
Being fishermen andtrappers, the French did a fine

347
00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:46.430
job of mapping this entirenervous system of the rivers,

348
00:35:46.430 --> 00:35:49.430
but beyond them they simply putin the names of Indian tribes

349
00:35:49.430 --> 00:35:53.430
the Miamis, the Illinois, theSioux.

350
00:35:53.430 --> 00:35:57.700
Down here in what is now theUnited States they did not plancolonies,

351
00:35:57.700 --> 00:36:01.300
they settled allays close to theriver, way stations,

352
00:36:01.300 --> 00:36:05.270
or what we might call retailcenters for the down rivertraffic,

353
00:36:05.270 --> 00:36:11.400
bearing fur and hides and timberdown to the port of New Orleans.

354
00:36:11.400 --> 00:36:17.170
But if they found some localuseful product a mineral salt,

355
00:36:17.170 --> 00:36:18.900
then they would stop and make atown.

356
00:36:18.900 --> 00:36:24.430
And we're in one now, at St.Genevieve, Missouri on theMississippi,

357
00:36:24.430 --> 00:36:29.630
which is one of the last toretain the flavor and the lookof provincial France.

358
00:36:29.630 --> 00:36:32.430
We're in the house of a FrenchCanadian born merchant,

359
00:36:32.430 --> 00:36:35.500
this is the desk where he didhis accounts;

360
00:36:35.500 --> 00:36:39.570
here are the steps going up tothe bedroom, which was also usedfor winter storage.

361
00:36:39.570 --> 00:36:42.900
I think this is the mostcharacteristic French house

362
00:36:42.900 --> 00:36:51.070
now remaining in the MississippiValley.

363
00:36:51.070 --> 00:36:57.830
What the French found here waslead -veins of lead ofincredible richness.

364
00:36:57.830 --> 00:37:01.130
So they brought in two hundredFrench miners

365
00:37:01.130 --> 00:37:05.070
and imported five hundred negroslaves from Santo Domingo.

366
00:37:05.070 --> 00:37:08.530
And they carried the lead forshipping down the Mississippi,

367
00:37:08.530 --> 00:37:11.500
across the flat lands that laysouth of this city

368
00:37:11.500 --> 00:37:15.270
which they called Le Grand Champ-the big field.

369
00:37:15.270 --> 00:37:19.370
The French usually started witha fort and a few soldiers,

370
00:37:19.370 --> 00:37:23.330
but they found this village,straggling village indefensible,

371
00:37:23.330 --> 00:37:28.270
so they palisade the houses andit was everyman for himself.

372
00:37:28.270 --> 00:37:31.370
However, they prospered, andthey made a country town.

373
00:37:31.370 --> 00:37:34.270
They brought over theirmissionaries and priests,

374
00:37:34.270 --> 00:37:37.170
planted their familiar vines andshrubs - in fact,

375
00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:42.200
imported their culture,including a useful strain of thrift.

376
00:37:42.200 --> 00:37:48.000
The first man who owned thishouse prospered exceedingly, aman named Louis Bolduc.

377
00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:54.170
And he kept his money stored inthe cellars there. One time anAmerican merchant came through.

378
00:37:54.170 --> 00:37:56.970
And they took a bet as to whowas the wealthier.

379
00:37:56.970 --> 00:38:04.200
When Bolduc sent for a servantand ordered up a half a bushelbasket to measure his silver,

380
00:38:04.200 --> 00:38:06.030
the American paid up.

381
00:38:06.030 --> 00:38:09.530
Now this place, St. Genevieve,in the late eighteenth century

382
00:38:09.530 --> 00:38:12.170
was a little Paris for theMississippi Valley.

383
00:38:12.170 --> 00:38:15.800
And parents with aspirations togentility

384
00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:19.600
sent their children here tolearn to be good Catholics,

385
00:38:19.600 --> 00:38:21.570
to learn to speak good French.

386
00:38:21.570 --> 00:38:25.430
And one boy who came all the wayfrom Pittsburgh remembered veryvividly

387
00:38:25.430 --> 00:38:30.200
that he had, after Sunday mass, attended a school ofmanners where -

388
00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:35.300
he said -we learned thetwo elements of true politeness;

389
00:38:35.300 --> 00:38:37.300
grace and self-denial.

390
00:38:51.870 --> 00:38:58.270
On the whole the French Catholicinfluence was instructive andbenign.

391
00:38:58.270 --> 00:39:01.330
It was rarely so in the Spanishsouth-west.

392
00:39:13.330 --> 00:39:17.200
The Conquistadors had been sentas the sword of the pope.

393
00:39:17.200 --> 00:39:21.730
And today in southern Arizona,the Papago Indians go off toworship

394
00:39:21.730 --> 00:39:25.330
in one of the great imperialmonuments left by the Spanish,

395
00:39:25.330 --> 00:39:28.530
the church of San Xavier delBac,

396
00:39:28.530 --> 00:39:34.530
where primitive Indianspractice the most sophisticatedrituals of Europe.

397
00:39:48.130 --> 00:39:50.130
A chief of the Papagos.

