436
00:45:10.470 --> 00:45:15.700
In the unlikely event that twohundred million Americans wereever put up

437
00:45:15.700 --> 00:45:25.930
against a wall at gunpoint andordered to name one Frenchmanwho had meant most to America,

438
00:45:25.930 --> 00:45:29.530
I think the name would be theMarquis de Lafayette.

439
00:45:29.530 --> 00:45:33.070
A young French nobleman, 19years old, newly married,

440
00:45:33.070 --> 00:45:36.230
forbidden to leave France whenthe War of Independence brokeout,

441
00:45:36.230 --> 00:45:41.130
he escaped to America. "Myheart", he said, "enlisted inthe cause of liberty".

442
00:45:41.130 --> 00:45:45.530
George Washington was moved byhis charm and bravery. He wasmade a Major-General,

443
00:45:45.530 --> 00:45:49.070
was wounded, fought in the lastengagement at Yorktown,

444
00:45:49.070 --> 00:45:52.900
and was given the freedom of agrateful republic.

445
00:45:52.900 --> 00:45:55.430
He went home to fight in theFrench Revolution

446
00:45:55.430 --> 00:46:00.130
for what he believed was asimilar brave cause.

447
00:46:00.130 --> 00:46:04.130
He was too liberal for theRoyalists, and too moderate forthe Republicans,

448
00:46:04.130 --> 00:46:06.170
and he was thrown into adungeon.

449
00:46:06.170 --> 00:46:09.700
His wife asked to join him thereand she was allowed to.

450
00:46:09.700 --> 00:46:15.730
And they stayed five years,which broke her in spirit and in body.

451
00:46:15.730 --> 00:46:19.070
They came to be buried togetherin a small graveyard in Paris,

452
00:46:19.070 --> 00:46:27.200
and in time by their side laytheir only son, GeorgeWashington Lafayette.

453
00:46:27.200 --> 00:46:32.700
No country has been than Francein having in the person of oneman

454
00:46:32.700 --> 00:46:36.270
such a permanent investmentin American goodwill.

